2. JFrog SaaS + AWS	JFrog Cloud hosted on AWS region

JFrog Cloud (SaaS) on AWS
JFrog Cloud is fully managed — no EC2 to provision. JFrog runs the infrastructure on AWS for you.

1. Sign Up / Create Instance
Go to https://jfrog.com/start-free
Choose JFrog Cloud (not Self-Hosted)
Select AWS as the cloud provider
Pick your AWS region (e.g., us-east-1, eu-west-1)
Choose a subdomain: https://yourcompany.jfrog.io
Free tier includes 2 GB storage + 10 GB transfer/month.

2. Connect Your AWS Workloads
CLI / SDK authentication

# Set up JFrog CLI
curl -fL https://install-cli.jfrog.io | sh

jf config add \
  --url https://yourcompany.jfrog.io \
  --user your@email.com \
  --password <API_KEY_OR_TOKEN> \
  --interactive=false

Docker login

docker login yourcompany.jfrog.io \
  -u your@email.com \
  -p <API_TOKEN>

3. Push/Pull Artifacts from EC2 or CI

# Push a Docker image
docker tag myapp:latest yourcompany.jfrog.io/docker-local/myapp:latest
docker push yourcompany.jfrog.io/docker-local/myapp:latest

# Pull
docker pull yourcompany.jfrog.io/docker-local/myapp:latest

# Push a generic artifact
jf rt upload "build/*.zip" my-generic-repo/releases/

4. Use as npm / pip / Maven Proxy
JFrog Cloud acts as a caching proxy for public registries — reduces egress costs and adds security scanning.

# npm
npm config set registry https://yourcompany.jfrog.io/artifactory/api/npm/npm-virtual/

# pip
pip install --index-url \
  https://your@email.com:<TOKEN>@yourcompany.jfrog.io/artifactory/api/pypi/pypi-virtual/simple \
  requests

5. IAM / OIDC Integration (EC2 / CodeBuild / GitHub Actions)
Avoid hardcoded credentials — use OIDC tokens:

# GitHub Actions example
- name: Authenticate to JFrog
  uses: jfrog/setup-jfrog-cli@v4
  env:
    JF_URL: https://yourcompany.jfrog.io
  with:
    oidc-provider-name: github   # configured in JFrog Platform → Security → OIDC

For EC2 with an IAM role, use JFrog Access Token stored in AWS Secrets Manager:

aws secretsmanager get-secret-value \
  --secret-id jfrog/api-token \
  --query SecretString --output text | \
  docker login yourcompany.jfrog.io -u ci-user --password-stdin

6. Network Peering (Optional, Enterprise+)
For low-latency, private connectivity between your AWS VPC and JFrog Cloud:

Go to JFrog Platform → Administration → Network
Enable AWS PrivateLink (Enterprise+ plan)
Accept the VPC Endpoint in your AWS account under VPC → Endpoint Services

Key Differences vs Self-Hosted
JFrog Cloud (SaaS)	Self-Hosted on EC2
Maintenance	JFrog manages	You manage
Upgrades	Automatic	Manual
Cost model	Subscription by storage/transfer	EC2 + EBS costs
PrivateLink	Enterprise+	Native VPC
Data residency	Region-locked	Full control

